United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gedge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English  <i>gegge</i>, a derogatory term used for both men and women, though the present pronunciation, rhyming with  <i>ledge</i>, is unexplained."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Gedge was born in 1490, in Sheffield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Bardfield. He died about 1530, in London, England, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1490–about 1530":"1490–umbes 1530","1494–1539":"1494–1539","1516–1555":"1516–1555","1490–1530":"1490–1530","1555":"1555","1530":"1530","1494":"1494","about 1530":"umbes 1530","1490":"1490","1539":"1539","1516":"1516","Sheffield, Essex, England":"Shenfield, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sheffield, Yorkshire, England":"Sheffield, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",